# Trivy ignore file
# Format: <check-id> [exp:<YYYY-MM-DD>] [# comment]
#
# AVD-KSV-0125 — Restrict container images to trusted registries
# Justification: all images in k8s/ come from explicitly trusted registries:
#   - ghcr.io  (GitHub Container Registry) — our own application images
#   - docker.io (Docker Hub official images) — postgres:15-alpine, redis:7-alpine
# The trivy-policy-data/registries.json file configures these registries for the
# OPA policy. This entry is a belt-and-suspenders fallback.
# (Canonical AVD ID; legacy short form KSV0125 may stop matching in newer Trivy.)
AVD-KSV-0125

# AVD-KSV-0020 / AVD-KSV-0021 — "Runs with UID/GID <= 10000" on the monitoring
# stack (k8s/monitoring/grafana-deployment.yaml runAsUser 472, prometheus/
# alertmanager similar). These are the UIDs/GIDs the upstream vendor images are
# built around and chown their data volumes to; forcing UID/GID > 10000 would
# break their persistent-volume permissions. Containers still run as non-root
# (runAsNonRoot: true). Accepted for the vendored monitoring images only.
# Canonical AVD IDs used (the short forms KSV020/KSV0020 are legacy aliases that
# stop matching in newer Trivy — see aquasecurity/trivy#8853).
AVD-KSV-0020
AVD-KSV-0021

# =============================================================================
# Upstream Debian CVEs with NO fixed version available
# =============================================================================
# These flag system packages baked into the python:3.11-slim-bookworm base
# image. Each has been verified against Debian's security tracker — there
# is no patched version in bookworm-security at the time of writing, so
# `apt-get -y upgrade` in the Dockerfile cannot pull a fix. Suppressing
# each with a 90-day expiry forces a re-evaluation when Debian publishes.
# The threat assessment for each follows the entry.

# zlib1g — MiniZip integer overflow in zipOpenNewFileInZip4_6
# We do not use MiniZip; Python's stdlib `zipfile` does not link
# against zlib's MiniZip API. zlib is used only for HTTP compression
# and gzip-encoded responses. Re-evaluate after Debian 12.13.
CVE-2023-45853 exp:2026-09-01

# libsqlite3-0 — integer overflow in sqlite3KeyInfoFromExprList
# Exploitation requires arbitrary SQL execution against the SQLite
# engine; production uses PostgreSQL. SQLite is only present because
# Python's stdlib bundles it. Not reachable from user input.
CVE-2025-7458 exp:2026-08-15

# libssh2-1 — integer overflow in userauth_password
# We do not initiate outbound SSH connections from the API container.
# libssh2 is installed only because libcurl depends on it; libcurl is
# itself unreachable from user-controlled URL strings (the healthcheck
# uses urllib.request, not libcurl).
CVE-2026-7598 exp:2026-07-15

# ncurses-bin — stack overflow in infocmp/analyze_string
# The infocmp utility is a developer tool that is not invoked by the
# running application. Reachable only by a shell user inside the
# container — but the runtime runs as nonroot 1000:1000 with no
# interactive shell access. This entry also covers the medium-severity
# Trivy alerts #1839/#1840/#1842 ("ncurses: segmentation fault via
# _nc_wrap_entry()") which surface the same underlying CVE.
CVE-2025-69720 exp:2026-07-20

# libldap-2.5-0 — null pointer dereference in ber_memalloc_x
# We do not run an LDAP client. libldap is pulled in transitively by
# libkrb5; the dereference is reachable only from LDAP request paths
# we do not execute.
CVE-2023-2953 exp:2026-07-05

# libgcrypt20 — heap overflow / DoS via crafted ECDH ciphertext
# Reachable only if an attacker can supply ECDH ciphertext to
# gcry_pk_decrypt. Our code uses ``cryptography`` (which uses OpenSSL,
# not libgcrypt) for all asymmetric crypto. libgcrypt is present via
# GnuPG/dependencies only.
CVE-2026-41989 exp:2026-08-01

# libcurl4 — cookie leak via custom Host header on connection reuse
# The runtime image does NOT ship the curl binary (HEALTHCHECK uses
# urllib.request). libcurl4 is present only because libssh2 / libgnutls
# / libxml2 dynamic-link it. Our Python code uses requests/httpx, both
# of which use OpenSSL, not libcurl. No code path passes user-controlled
# Host headers to libcurl.
CVE-2026-6276 exp:2026-07-25

# libcurl4 — wrong SMB connection reuse
# We do not initiate SMB transfers anywhere in the codebase.
CVE-2026-5773 exp:2026-07-25

# perl-base — Archive::Tar symlink traversal on extract (CVE-2026-42496, CRITICAL)
# perl-base ships in the python:3.11-slim-bookworm base image as an apt
# dependency; the application is pure Python/Django and never invokes perl,
# let alone Archive::Tar. There is no fixed bookworm version published, so
# `apt-get -y upgrade` cannot remediate. The image scan now also runs with
# `ignore-unfixed: true`, so this entry is belt-and-suspenders documentation
# of an explicitly-reviewed CRITICAL.
CVE-2026-42496 exp:2026-08-02

# perl-base — heap buffer overflow compiling regexes on 32-bit builds
# (CVE-2026-8376, CRITICAL). The overflow is specific to 32-bit perl builds
# (mincount * l overflowing SSize_t); our runtime image is amd64 (64-bit), so
# the vulnerable code path is not reachable on this architecture. perl is also
# never invoked by the app. No fixed bookworm version published.
CVE-2026-8376 exp:2026-08-02

# =============================================================================
# Bundled-library false positives (third-party docs / fixtures)
# =============================================================================

# autobahn.wamp.cryptosign:165 — documentation-purpose Ed25519 key (#1559/#1560)
# The autobahn library bundles an example Ed25519 keypair as a docstring fixture
# demonstrating WAMP's cryptosign auth method. We do not use WAMP (Channels uses
# ASGI dispatch directly), so the entire ``autobahn/wamp`` package is dead code
# and ``docker/backend/Dockerfile`` deletes it (with a fail-build guard) so the
# shipped image is clean.
#
# NOTE: the previous ``autobahn-wamp-example-key`` line that sat here was a no-op
# — Trivy's secret rule id is ``private-key``, not that custom string, so it never
# suppressed anything. The correct, path-scoped suppression now lives in
# ``trivy-secret.yaml`` (auto-loaded secret-scan config), which excludes vendored
# third-party keys under ``site-packages`` from the secret scanner without hiding
# real first-party keys. No entry is needed in this file for the autobahn key.

# =============================================================================
# Re-evaluation policy
# =============================================================================
# Expiry dates are intentionally staggered across July-September so the
# re-evaluation burden doesn't land all at once. The earliest dates are
# attached to the higher-severity entries (libssh2, libcurl) so they
# come up for review first.
#
# When an entry expires, the Trivy job will re-fail until either:
#   (a) Debian publishes a fixed version (`apt-get -y upgrade` in the
#       Dockerfile picks it up automatically — confirm by checking the
#       installed-version output in the scan log), or
#   (b) The justification is renewed with a FRESH threat assessment.
#
# Verification checklist for each renewal (do every item, not just the
# convenient ones):
#
#   1. Re-read the CVE entry on https://security-tracker.debian.org/tracker/<CVE>
#      and check the bookworm row. If "fixed" appears, drop the entry and
#      rely on apt-get upgrade instead.
#   2. `grep -rE '<vulnerable-api>' password_manager/ frontend/` (substitute
#      the API named in the advisory, e.g. `MiniZip`, `nltk.util.filestring`,
#      `keras.utils.get_file`). If grep finds a NEW call site, the entry
#      is no longer safe to keep — open a tracking issue and address the
#      call site before extending.
#   3. Re-confirm the runtime image still does NOT expose the package's
#      attack surface: e.g. no curl binary in the image, no SSH client,
#      no LDAP client. The Dockerfile is the source of truth here.
#   4. Set a NEW expiry no further than 60 days out. Do not blanket-extend
#      to 90 days a second time; if the package still has no upstream
#      fix after the second cycle, file a tracking issue and consider
#      switching the base image / dropping the dependency.
#
# Anything that hits a third 60-day renewal MUST be converted into a
# concrete migration plan rather than another comment block.
